ide of New York State's upper Hudson River. The area within three thousand feet of the fort became the village of Beverwijck. From the time of its establishment until 1664, when the English conquered New Netherland and changed the name of the settlement to Albany, Beverwijck underwent rapid development as newly wealthy traders, craftsmen, and other workers built houses, roads, bridges, and a school, as well as a number of inns. A well-organized system of poor relief also helped less wealthy settlers survive in the harsh colonial conditions. Venema's careful research shows that although Beverwijck resembled villages in the Dutch Republic in many ways, it quickly took on features of the new, "American" society that was already coming into being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDutch AmericanszNew York (State)zAlbanyxHistoryy17th century. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezNew York (State)zAlbany. 0aIndians of North AmericazNew York (State)zAlbanyxHistoryy17th century. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079148501940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791485019423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791485019/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles